  "text": "Django's middleware stack construction is implemented in django/core/handlers/base.py through the BaseHandler.load_middleware() method (lines 27-104). The critical insight is that middleware is loaded in REVERSED order from settings.MIDDLEWARE (line 41: 'for middleware_path in reversed(settings.MIDDLEWARE)'), creating an inside-out call chain similar to WSGI but with explicit reversal.\n\nEach middleware instance is initialized with a get_response callable that represents the next handler in the chain. The middleware is wrapped with exception handling via convert_exception_to_response() (django/core/handlers/exception.py, lines 25-61), ensuring no uncaught exceptions escape any middleware.\n\nThe MiddlewareMixin class (django/utils/deprecation.py, lines 275-332) provides the base interface for middleware. Its __call__() method (lines 302-312) executes the middleware lifecycle: process_request() -> get_response() -> process_response(). The async equivalent __acall__() (lines 314-331) maintains the same pattern with async/await semantics.\n\nDifferent middleware methods are processed in different orders:\n1. process_view middleware (line 79-83): Inserted at position 0 (reverse iteration order)\n2. process_template_response middleware (line 84-89): Appended (normal iteration order)\n3. process_exception middleware (line 90-95): Appended (normal iteration order)\n\nThese separate lists are executed in _get_response() (lines 176-228) and _get_response_async() (lines 230-300):\n- process_view: Iterated in normal order (line 186-191)\n- process_template_response: Iterated in normal order (line 211-220)\n- process_exception: Iterated in normal order (line 363-366)\n\nThe request/response chain differs from standard WSGI middleware stacking because Django separates the concerns: request processing, view wrapping, template response processing, and exception handling are handled in distinct phases rather than as a single nested wrapper. The WSGIHandler (django/core/handlers/wsgi.py, lines 113-144) initializes middleware on instantiation (line 118) and calls into the chain via get_response() (line 124), while ASGIHandler (django/core/handlers/asgi.py, lines 143-230) uses async initialization with is_async=True (line 152).\n\nThe convert_exception_to_response() wrapper ensures each middleware layer cannot raise unhandled exceptions to the next middleware, making the chain safer and more predictable than raw WSGI middleware stacking."
}

